Vararg parameters.

A star after a parameter type marks it as a vararg. The caller can then pass any number of arguments of that type, and inside the method the parameter arrives as a sequence of that type.

Picture a join-all method that takes a separator and then a vararg of strings, and returns the parts joined by the separator. A caller can pass the separator and then as many individual strings as they like, and they all collect into one sequence inside the method.

There is one extra move worth knowing — passing an existing collection as the varargs. You cannot just hand a list to a vararg parameter directly, because the method expects loose arguments, not one list. Instead you append a star to the argument at the call site, which spreads the collection out into individual arguments. So with a list of tokens already in hand, you call join-all with the separator and then the tokens followed by a star, and the list is splatted into the vararg. In Scala 2 that splat was written with a colon and an underscore-star; the Scala 3 form is just the trailing star.
